AI-Driven Robust Estimation of Battery State of Health and Remaining Useful Life: A Multi‑Fidelity Physics‑Informed Deep Learning Approach

Version 0.4

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

The widespread adoption of electric vehicles (EVs) hinges on the reliable and safe operation of lithium‑ion batteries, whose performance degrades over time. Accurate estimation of State of Health (SOH) and Remaining Useful Life (RUL) is critical for predictive maintenance, warranty management, and second‑life applications. While recent advances in deep learning have shown promise, existing models often fail under real‑world conditions due to three fundamental limitations: (i) reliance on raw voltage/current/temperature signals that lack direct electrochemical interpretability, (ii) absence of physical constraints leading to non‑physiological predictions (e.g., increasing capacity), and (iii) lack of uncertainty quantification, which is essential for safety‑critical decisions.

This thesis proposes a hybrid physics‑informed deep learning framework that addresses these gaps and introduces two major extensions that significantly enhance its practical utility. First, raw sensor data are transformed into Incremental Capacity (IC) curves using Savitzky–Golay smoothing, extracting peak features (height, position, area) that directly correlate with degradation modes such as Loss of Lithium Inventory and Loss of Active Material. A CNN‑Transformer architecture then processes these IC peak sequences: convolutional layers capture local shape variations, while transformers model long‑term degradation trends over hundreds of cycles. To enforce physical consistency, a multi‑fidelity physics‑informed loss integrates an Equivalent Circuit Model (ECM) constraint, linking predicted SOH to internal resistance via Ohm’s law, and a monotonicity penalty that is selectively masked during rest periods to allow capacity recovery. Uncertainty is quantified through a Bayesian output head (via Monte Carlo Dropout), yielding probabilistic SOH estimates and full RUL distributions.

Building on this foundation, the framework is extended in two critical directions:

1. Multi‑Task Learning for Comprehensive Prognostics – A shared encoder feeds multiple prediction heads that simultaneously estimate SOH, RUL, the knee‑point (the cycle at which degradation accelerates), and the short‑term capacity trajectory over the next N cycles. This multi‑task formulation improves generalization by leveraging inductive biases across related tasks and provides a complete picture of battery health.
2. Cross‑Chemistry Domain Adaptation – To bridge the gap between laboratory cells (typically NMC/LCO) and diverse real‑world chemistries (LFP, NMC, Na‑ion), we incorporate an adversarial domain adaptation module that aligns feature distributions across source and target domains. By leveraging relaxation voltage curves as chemistry‑invariant signatures, the model achieves strong zero‑shot and few‑shot transfer performance, paving the way for a universal battery health backbone.

The framework is validated (in silico) on multiple public datasets (NASA, CALCE, Oxford, MIT, XJTU) and simulated real‑world profiles. Expected outcomes include: (i) SOH prediction with <1.5% RMSE, (ii) physically plausible outputs (zero unphysical increases), (iii) well‑calibrated uncertainty intervals (PICP >90%), (iv) accurate knee‑point detection and trajectory forecasting, and (v) successful cross‑chemistry transfer with minimal fine‑tuning. This work advances the state of the art by unifying electrochemical feature engineering, temporal deep learning, physical constraints, uncertainty quantification, multi‑task learning, and domain adaptation into a single robust framework, paving the way for reliable battery health monitoring in real‑world EVs.

