Chapter 5: Theoretical Results and Expected Outcomes

5.1 Introduction

This chapter presents the anticipated theoretical results of the proposed framework for battery State of Health (SOH) and Remaining Useful Life (RUL) estimation. Since the thesis focuses on algorithmic development and theoretical contributions, we derive expected performance characteristics based on mathematical properties of the models, known results from the literature, and theoretical analysis of the proposed components. The aim is to demonstrate, through reasoning, why the proposed methodology is expected to outperform existing approaches and to provide insights into its behavior under ideal conditions. Section 5.2 discusses expected SOH estimation accuracy, Section 5.3 analyzes the impact of physics‑informed losses, Section 5.4 addresses uncertainty quantification, Section 5.5 covers multi‑task learning benefits, Section 5.6 examines domain adaptation performance, Section 5.7 discusses explainability, and Section 5.8 summarizes the key theoretical contributions.

5.2 Expected SOH Estimation Accuracy

5.2.1 Benefit of Incremental Capacity Features

The transformation of raw voltage–current–temperature measurements into Incremental Capacity (IC) curves extracts features that are directly linked to electrochemical degradation modes such as loss of lithium inventory (LLI) and loss of active material (LAM) [11,12]. The IC peaks evolve monotonically with aging: their positions shift, heights decrease, and areas shrink. By providing these physically meaningful features as input, the model is relieved from learning these complex transformations from raw data.

Theoretical Justification: From an information‑theoretic perspective, let X_{\text{raw}} be the raw signal and X_{\text{IC}} be the ICA‑transformed features. The mutual information I(X_{\text{IC}}; \text{SOH}) is greater than I(X_{\text{raw}}; \text{SOH}) because the ICA transformation is a deterministic function that discards noise and irrelevant variations while preserving degradation‑relevant information [13]. By the data processing inequality, I(X_{\text{raw}}; \text{SOH}) \geq I(X_{\text{IC}}; \text{SOH}) if the transformation were arbitrary, but here the transformation is designed to enhance the signal‑to‑noise ratio, effectively increasing the mutual information with the target. Therefore, any model using IC features will have a lower bound on achievable error (via Fano's inequality) that is lower than that of raw features.

Expected Outcome: The proposed model with ICA features will achieve SOH estimation RMSE below 1.5% on benchmark datasets, outperforming models using raw features by at least 0.5% absolute RMSE.

5.2.2 Superiority of Hybrid CNN‑Transformer Architecture

The hybrid architecture combines the strengths of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and Transformers. The CNN layers act as local feature extractors, capturing the shape of IC peaks within each cycle. This is analogous to applying a learned filter bank that is optimized for the task, which is known to be more effective than handcrafted features when sufficient data are available [14]. The Transformer encoder then models long‑range dependencies across cycles, using self‑attention to weigh the importance of past cycles.

Theoretical Justification: The Transformer's self‑attention mechanism provides direct connections between any two cycles, mitigating the vanishing gradient problem that plagues RNNs when the number of cycles exceeds a few hundred [15]. The attention weights can be interpreted as importance scores, allowing the model to focus on cycles where significant degradation events occurred. The capacity of the Transformer to capture long‑range dependencies is characterized by its effective receptive field, which is the entire sequence length, unlike RNNs where it is limited by the number of unrolled steps.

Expected Outcome: The hybrid CNN‑Transformer will achieve lower RMSE than LSTM, CNN‑LSTM, and pure Transformer baselines, with improvements most pronounced in the later stages of life where long‑term dependencies are critical.

